		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Thu, Mar 24th 1:36 PM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=1111660459530331144&num=21&post=1&replyto=1111689350369119581"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1111689350369119581></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=307780"><span id=Scholar>Thoryndar</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />71 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.08]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Thoryndar&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>First, I would like to list my credentials.<br><br>I am an A+ Certified hardware technician.<br><br>I am working on my MCSE.<br><br>My job title is On-Call Computer Systems Administrator / LAN Technician, and I have held this title for 3 1/2 years. Part of my job responsibility is to purchase equpiment for and end user base of over 400 people.<br><br>I could have easily built my own computer. I chose not to.<br><br>I, on a weekly basis, purchase at least one Dell system for end users in my office. When it came time for me to purchase my own new system, I chose Dell as well.<br><br>Why?<br><br>Because they are reliable, rock solid, you get what you pay for, and I will almost guarantee you will not the customer service and technical support if you choose to build your own PC. Of the 100+ systems that I have personally purchased, set up, and deployed on our network, only a single one of them had a problem, which was solved by downloading a patch from Microsoft - it was NOT a hardware related issue.<br><br>Alienware, while a great system, is extremely overpriced, and designed more for a high-end gamer.<br><br>If you want to be able to do something more than just play games on your PC, you will want something that is capable of ALL aspects.<br><br>That being said, I will list what I personally chose.<br><br>Dimension 8300 Series<br><br>Intel Board - 800 FSB<br>Pentium 4 3.0ghz with HT<br>2 gig DDR Memory<br>Radeon 9800 XT Graphics Card<br>Intel GigE Ethernet<br>2 120 Gig SATA Hard Drives<br>52x CD/RW<br>52x DVD+-R<br>8 USB 2.0/1.1 ports<br>Floppy Drive<br>Soundblaster (THX Certified) Audio Card<br>Microsoft XP Professional SP1 OS<br><br>For the record:<br><br>My system has never once crashed in an application.<br><br>It has never locked up.<br><br>It has NEVER been close to being out of RAM.<br><br>I have massive amounts of storage, and room for expandibility.<br><br>While playing DOOM III, the system runs at max graphics capability, with NO HANG, and NO delay.<br><br>If you are building a gaming machine, please keep the following in mind:<br><br>If you do not have a separate graphics card, you are asking for poor performance all the way around, because it will take from your existing RAM to make up for what it doesn't have. Get a video card. I personally like ATI chipsets, because they allow for a sanctioned overclocking, and are DX9 compatible. NVidia is DX9 compatible, but only after ATI did it first.<br><br>Windows XP, just to operate needs about 128 mb of Ram. To operate smoothly, 256 is reccomended. at 512, you will see a performance boost. If you are a hardcore gamer, I would reccomend NOTHING less than 1 gig.<br><br>You will **NOT** be able to see a dramatic increase between a processor that runs at 3.0 vs 3.2. Don't pay extra for it - it is simply not worth it.<br><br>The cost of my system, including a monitor, shipping and handling was just under 3 grand. After I spoke with my account rep, the price was lowered to 2,400. The majority of that increase was caused by the additional 1 gig if RAM I had put into the system, and an upgrade to the monitor, but because I had been giving the guy such an enormous amount of business, he gave me a break.<br><br>You can get, essentially the same system as I have, for probably in the neighborhood of 1.2 - 1.5k, not including a monitor.<br><br>What it comes down to is personal preferance, personal need, and how much you actually plan on doing with it : take this into consideration. You want something that will handle today's needs, with a lot of time to handle the future as well.<br><br>Hope I helped in some small way, and if you need additional help, please feel free to send me a private message.</p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br />Brell Serilis</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from Chicago, IL</td></tr></table>
