		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Thu, Mar 24th 2:57 PM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=1111660459530331144&num=21&post=1&replyto=1111694215242053393"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1111694215242053393></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=247125"><span id=Scholar>Jiggidyjay of the Seven Seas</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br /><img alt="Avatar" height="73" width="100" src="/uf/Jiggidyjay/Avatar2.jpg"><br /><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />1593 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.34]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Jiggidyjay&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>I fully support building your own system. I enjoy it. It's a lot of fun (if you're into that kind of thing) and the satisfaction level is high. But....<br><br>If you're new to building systems or don't have a lot of knowledge on what to look for or if you don't keep up with the PC world trends, you can get yourself into trouble.<br><br>It's easy for someone that keeps up with the trends to say &quot;Do your homework&quot; or &quot;check these sites&quot; (not trying to single you out Paradime, just making a point), but for the novice, it's still a bunch of &quot;gobeldy-guck&quot;. To the novice, big numbers usually signify big performance, and those that are in the &quot;know&quot; know that that isn't always the truth. It's easy to get confused with all of the terminology and accidentally buy things you either don't need, that aren't compatible, or forget to buy things that you DO need (remember the first time you ever bought a printer, then realized when you got home that you had to buy a cable too?).<br><br>That's the biggest reason I will tell anyone that's completely new to building a system but wants one quickly to buy a &quot;built&quot; system. I specify built, because there's a difference between &quot;built&quot; and &quot;premade&quot;. Of course, if you go this route, you have to be careful which manufacturer you choose. Barring any of the very highend gaming machine manufacturers (Alienware, Falcon West, etc, since the OP specified not paying WAY too much), my first suggestion would be a Dell. I use Dells A LOT (government work...) and I don't really run into any problems. You'll have to do a restart once in a while when program screws up or something, but everything works pretty solidly. I actually own a Dell 8400 and I like it a lot. No problems, and I've had it for about 3 months now. One of the nice things about Dell is they use &quot;real&quot; components, namebrand stuff, and you can usually upgrade their PCs without much fuss.<br><br>On the otherside of the coin, you have companies like HP and Compaq. They are notorius for having rediculous case design that doesn't allow for upgrades, using motherboards that are YEARS old and already maxed out on RAM when you get them, sneaking in onboard video or a cheap PCI card (you're a novice, you won't know the difference, right?)... the list goes on. I don't know ANYONE that has ever been happy with an HP or Compaq machine.<br><br>Building your own rig and buying a &quot;built&quot; rig each has it's own pluses and minuses of course. <br><br>When you build your own, you get that satisfaction of doing it, you get to put EXACTLY what you want on it, and you get an actual Windows CD (just keep in mind that you don't own that software....). The downside is you typcially won't get any support from anywhere. It's possible you can get limited support for individual components, but if something just isn't working right and you or your friends can't figure it out, you might end up paying a butt-ton to take it to somewhere to get checked out (where they'll probably just plug in something you forgot, and still charge you the 150 for it).<br><br>Buying a built machine is nice because you get it, you plug it in, pop in your CD (which is a restore disk, so not as cool as getting an actual windows CD IMO), fill in the boxes and you're set. 15 minutes tops. If something goes wrong, you have the phone numbers to call and hopefully get it taken of quickly and painlessly. The downsides are that some systems are difficult to upgrade, and you'll pay a little more to get that convienence and support.<br><br>Whichever you choose, take your time and don't rush your decision too much. If you do decide to go with a built machine, I suggest checking out the Dell refurbished machines. My 8400 with 3.2 gig, 1 gig DDR, PCI-E (only an ATI X300 though), wireless keyboard and mouse, double layer DVD-writer + 2nd DVD drive and much more cost me a grand total of 900 bucks. Somebody sent the entire thing back because the keyboard they had had gotten broken in transit (supposedly), so Dell had to sell it as a used computer (after they replaced the keyboard of course). Not too bad a deal if you ask me.</p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br /><a href="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1006062" target="akztarg">Jiggidyjay</a> - <span class="sm">Mr Ranger</span class="sm"><br><a href="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1003866" target="akztarg">Zingin Ansinging</a> - <span class="sm">Mr Bard of <a href="HTTP://firestormers.com/viewnews.php" target="akztarg">The Firestormers</a></span class="sm"><br><a href="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1006061" target="akztarg">Zolotaya</a> - <span class="sm">Ms Necro</span class="sm"><br><a href="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1189723" target="akztarg">Zeibis</a> - <span class="sm">Mr Monk</span class="sm"></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from the Oval Office.</td></tr></table>
